lves collecting evidence, examining witnesses, and potentially interrogating individuals.\n*   **Arrest (if applicable):** If the investigation reveals sufficient grounds, the police may arrest the accused person(s) in accordance with the provisions of BNSS.\n*   **Police Report (Charge Sheet/Final Report):** Upon completion of the investigation (usually within 60 or 90 days depending on the nature of the offence, as per BNSS provisions), the police will prepare a report.\n    *   If the investigation reveals sufficient evidence to prosecute, a **charge sheet** (under BNSS Section 193) is filed in court.\n    *   If there isn't enough evidence or the case is deemed false, a **final report** (or closure report) is filed, recommending closure of the case.\n*   **Court Proceedings:** If a charge sheet is filed, the court will take cognizance of the offence, and the judicial process, including trial, will begin.\n\n**3. Your Right to a Free FIR Copy:**\n\n*   As per BNSS Section 173(1), you have the right to receive a copy of the FIR **immediately and free of cost** from the police station where it was registered. This copy is essential for you to track the progress of your case.\n\n**4. Relevant Helpline Numbers:**\n\nIf you need urgent assistance or wish to report a situation:\n\n*   **Police Emergency:** 112 (All India Emergency Number)\n*   **Women's Helpline:** 1098 (Childline India) or 1090 (Women Power Line - specific states)\n*   **Cybercrime Helpline:** 1930\n*   **National Commission for Women (NCW) Helpline:** 7827170170 (for complaints related to women)\n\nUnderstanding these initial steps can help you navigate the legal system more effectively. Remember that your rights are protected by law.\n\n**Disclaimer:** This information is for general awareness and educational purposes only. The Indian legal system is complex, and specific advice depends on the unique facts and circumstances of each case. It is always strongly recommended to consult with a qualified 